sec.p:
We evaluated the association between expression of each autosomal gene and common cis genetic variants (within 1 Mb of the transcription start site) in each age group using linear regression models (“Materials and methods” section; Additional file 8). To minimize the impact of difference in statistical power between the two ages, we found and corrected for the number of hidden factors that maximized eQTL discovery separately in each age group (Fig. 3a and Additional file 1: Figure S7). After background noise correction, we detected 1326 eGenes, i.e., genes with at least one significant eQTL, at age 70 (8.5% of tested genes, FDR ≤ 1%) and 1264 eGenes at age 80. The depletion of eGenes at age 80, relative to age 70, was statistically significant (exact McNemar’s test; OR = 0.81, P=5.8×10−3).
