Gene expression changes in response to environmental exposures. To address the question of how stable eQTL effects are with age, we estimated the rate of replication of discovery eGenes from one age group in the other age group (Fig. 3b). We observed a high proportion of eGenes that replicated for each age, 92.2% (94.9%) of eGenes discovered at age 70 (80) replicated at age 80 (70) (FDR ≤ 10%), although the rate of replication was lower for eGenes discovered at age 70, compared to eGenes discovered at age 80 (binomial proportion test; \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
